INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1958, 5, '2013-07-02 13:14:04', '2013-07-02 17:14:04', '[well size="large"][heading type="h3" margintop="8px" marginbottom="8px" bordered="no" align="center"]\r\n\r\n[one_half last="no"]\r\n\r\n[testimonials][testimonial name="Mary Lou Guistini" gender="" company="CEO"]“Our mission is to serve individuals and small businesses by simplifying investing and by managing personalized portfolios at low cost."[/testimonial][/testimonials]\r\n\r\n[/one_half]\r\n\r\n[one_half last="yes"]\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.invessence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Invessence-Home-e1384794122956.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2531" alt="Smart Investing Made Simple" src="http://www.invessence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Invessence-Home.png" width="601" height="405" /></a>\r\n\r\n[/one_half]\r\n\r\n[/heading][/well]\r\n\r\n[one_fourth last="no"]\r\n\r\n[content_column fontawesomeicon="globe" title="Diversification"]\r\nOur portfolios are constructed with up to 20 different investments representing 4 core asset classes (Equities, Bonds, Commodities &amp; Cash).\r\n[/content_column]\r\n[/one_fourth]\r\n\r\n[one_fourth last="no"]\r\n[content_column fontawesomeicon="money" title="Minimize Cost"]\r\nThe lower your advisory and investment costs, the greater your share of investment returns.\r\n[/content_column]\r\n[/one_fourth]\r\n\r\n[one_fourth last="no"]\r\n[content_column fontawesomeicon="tasks" title="Discipline"]\r\nMaintaining the optimal portfolio requires time and attention. Invessence offers automatic rebalancing to help manage your strategy through different market cycles.\r\n[/content_column]\r\n[/one_fourth]\r\n\r\n[one_fourth last="yes"]\r\n[content_column fontawesomeicon="signal" title="Long Term"]\r\nThe market fluctuates over the short-term, focus on investing over the long-term. Our portfolios are built for investors with this strategy in mind.\r\n[/content_column]\r\n[/one_fourth]\r\n\r\n[heading type="h3" margintop="20px" marginbottom="10px" bordered="no" align="center"]Let us empower you to follow the Essence of Personal Investing.[/heading]', 'Invessence Home Page', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'coming-soon', '', '', '2013-11-27 19:46:18', '2013-11-27 19:46:18', '', 0, 'http://www.invessence.com/?page_id=1958', 0, 'page', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2041, 2, '2013-07-09 14:34:39', '2013-07-09 14:34:39', 'Here are the top 3 questions you should ask your financial advisor at your next face-to-face meeting.\n\n<b>1. Can you go over my recent monthly statement with me?<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-2044" alt="Investment" src="http://www.invessence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/image009.jpg" width="241" height="147" /></b>\n\nBrokerage companies often make monthly statements complicated out of choice. The less you understand about your account, the more free reign they have with your money. Don\'t hand over this power. It\'s not that difficult to understand investment statements if you are patient.\n\nSet-up an appointment and go over the positions that are held in your account and ask them why they are there. Ask them to show you the historical performance of your account for the last five years -- year by year. And ask them to compare your performance with that of the S&amp;P 500.\n\nUse your gut. If what they say makes sense and your performance as compared to the S&amp;P is acceptable, you probably are in good hands. But if the performance is way off or you just don\'t understand what your adviser is telling you, it might be time to make a change.\n\n<strong>2. W</strong><b>hy do you expect my current investment portfolio to be successful in both up and down stock markets?</b>\n\nEvery financial advisor’s ideas look good when the stock market is going up.  Make sure there is a plan in place when the economy and the stock market decline. With the current stock markets near all-time highs, this question is especially important now.\n\n<strong><strong>3.</strong> </strong><b>How are commissions or advisory fees taken out of my investment account?</b>\n\n<b> </b><b> </b>There is no monthly bill from your investment advisor like the one you receive from the electric company. It’s important that you understand how you are paying your current financial advisor in order to determine the quality of advice you are receiving.\n\nAnd don\'t worry if you still have questions later on or you forget something. If that happens, just march down to the advisor for a refresher. That\'s what their there for. It\'s your money. You have a right to understand how it’s being investment.', 'The Top 3 Questions Women Investors Should Ask Their Financial Advisors.', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-top-3-questions-women-investors-should-ask-their-financial-advisers', '', '', '2013-07-09 14:34:39', '2013-07-09 14:34:39', '', 0, 'http://www.invessence.com/?p=2041', 1, 'post', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2051, 2, '2013-07-09 13:03:29', '2013-07-09 13:03:29', 'How much are you paying in investment fees each year?\n\nA)      Less than &lt;1%\nB)      1 - 3%\nC)      3%&lt; or greater\n\nUnfortunately, the correct answer is C.\n\nYou need to be careful when asking an advisor what he or she charges. If the answer is “My fee is 1.5% percent,” he might be omitting the other expenses that you’ll also incur.\n\nIt’s estimated that the average investor pays 3% to 5% in <i>fees</i> each year! According to an article on Forbes.com, there are 6 different costs you should be aware of when purchasing a mutual fund 1) expense ratio, 2) transaction costs (brokerage commissions, market impact cost, and spread cost), 3) tax costs, 4) cash drag, 5) soft dollar cost and 6) advisory fees.\n\nFirst of all, it’s important that you understand all of these costs and how they affect your investments. Secondly, for the purpose of this blog, let’s focus on the two largest components of fees – the Expense Ratio &amp; Advisory Fee.\n\n<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-2045" alt="image013" src="http://www.invessence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/image013.jpg" width="269" height="161" />\n<ol>\n	<li>Expense Ratios - is the annual fee that all mutual funds or ETFs charge their shareholders. It is the cost to operate the fund and represents the percentage of the fund’s assets that go purely toward the expense of the daily operation of the fund. According to Morningstar, the average expense ratio for all mutual funds is 1.3% per year, although many are more than 2%.</li>\n	<li>Advisory Fees – a fee that an investment advisor charges for making investment decisions on behalf of a client. It is generally expressed as a percentage of assets. At some firms, the asset management fee is as high as 3% per year but most advisors typically charge 1.00% to 1.50%.</li>\n</ol>\nBy adding just these two components together the average expense ratio for all mutual funds plus the advisory fee (1.3% + 1.5% = 2.8%), you can see how ordinary investors can incur a total annual cost of 3% or more per year.\n\nAs a result, fee-conscious investors have flocked to <a href="http://www.google.com/">low-cost exchange traded funds</a> or decided to <a href="/Users/mehtap/Downloads/google.com">“Do-It-Yourself”</a> to keep those fees under control.', 'Paying in investment fees each year?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'paying-in-investment-fees-each-year', '', '', '2013-07-09 13:03:29', '2013-07-09 13:03:29', '', 0, 'http://www.invessence.com/?p=2051', 2, 'post', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2454, 2, '2013-10-09 15:06:25', '2013-10-09 19:06:25', '<a href="http://www.invessence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/image005.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-2020    alignleft" alt="" src="http://www.invessence.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/image005.jpg" width="199" height="131" /></a>\n\nThe lotus flower is a species of aquatic plant that is native to tropical Asian nations and embedded in the region’s religions, cultures and history. To many, the flower represents good fortune, self-awareness and enlightenment.\n\nThe flower grows in muddy water, and it is this environment that gives forth the flower’s most literal meaning: rising and blooming above the murk to achieve enlightenment.\n\nGiven that our motto at Invessence is “Smart Investing Made Simple”, we strive to simplify the “murk” of the financial markets and create a supportive environment to educate our clients and help them build a personalized investment plan. Each leaf represents a different asset class and it’s not the number of leaves that’s important but how each fits with one another that makes each flower unique.', 'What is the significance of the Invessence logo?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-the-meaning-of-the-invessence-logo', '', '', '2013-10-09 15:06:25', '2013-10-09 19:06:25', '', 0, 'http://www.invessence.com/?p=2454', 0, 'post', '', 0) ; 
